her you serve like Judas or like John.\n\n- C.S. Lewis, The Problem of Pain\n|\nThe universe offers you three things that money cannot buy: joy, love, and life.\n\n- Matshona\n|\nAll you have to do is put one word after another, and remember how great it feels to be a writer.\n\n- Stephanie\n|\nYou're my equal. And as much as that means we have each other's backs in public, it also means we that grant each other the gift of honesty - of truth.\n\n- Sarah J. Maas, A Court of Wings and Ruin\n|\nI had rather hear my dog bark at a crow, than a man swear he loves me.\n\n- William Shakespeare, Much Ado About Nothing\n|\nYour success and happiness lies in you. Resolve to keep happy, and your joy and you shall form an invicible host against difficulties.\n\n- Helen\n|\nGod, he was going to destroy her. But maybe for the first time in her life, she’d found a man worth shattering for.\n\n- Joey W. Hill, Worth the Wait\n|\nI hear them say 'Why do I miss someone I haven't even met?'How about not missing someone because it feels like they've been with you all along?\n\n- Nicola An, The Universe at Heartbeat\n|\nWhen you want to become great, you have to know what to do, I mean you must first determine what you were born to do.\n\n- Sunday Adelaja, The Mountain of Ignorance\n|\nWhat is essence of knowledge, if it does not change the way we act?\n\n- Lailah\n|\nToo late, I found you can't wait to become perfect, you got to go out and fall down and get up with everybody else.\n\n- Ray Bradbury, Something Wicked This Way Comes\n|\nBehind every person there lies a story which makes them what they are. Many a time, the story isn’t known to anybody.\n\n- Toffee, Finding Juliet\n|\nWithout a song, life is a sorrow.\n\n- Lailah\n|\nWhile art thrives on the blazing colours of scandal, literature blossoms on the dark soil of tragedy.\n\n- E.A. Bucchianeri, Brushstrokes of a Gadfly\n|\nThere is no Space or TimeOnly intensity, And tame thingsHave no immensity\n\n- Mina Loy, The Lost Lunar Baedeker: Poems of Mina Loy\n|\nThere are endless ways to thank the people who have contributed to your life. Dole out thanks, and your life will bloom.\n\n- Amy Leigh Mercree, Joyful Living: 101 Ways to Transform Your Spirit and Revitalize Your Life\n|\nFirst they ignore you, then they laugh at you, then they fight you, then you win.\n\n- Mahatma\n|\nHighs and lows make you feel that things matter, but they're nothing.\n\n- Jonathan Safran Foer, Extremely Loud and Incredibly Close\n|\nWithout courage, wisdom bears no fruit.\n\n- Baltasar\n|\nDon't even think of arguing with me. I'm an old woman and if you fight me about it, it could give me a heart attack.\n\n- Sara  Humphreys, The Amoveo Legacy\n|\nWomen only cut their hair in times of crisis... It's somethin' a woman always has the power to do, even when she loses control over everything else. Cuttin' hair is a cry for help.\n\n- Bella Pollen, Midnight Cactus\n|\nYou alwaysdrop by, to en-lighten my mind,when my wings arefeeling heavy &i've forgottenhow tofly.\n\n- Curtis\n|\nWhen Boredom comes, it is the time during which discovery is to be made. That is the time during which real effort (purushartha) can be made. But instead, people push it aside.\n\n- Dada\n|\nI will complain, yet praise;I will bewail, approve:And all my sowre-sweet dayesI will lament, and love.\n\n- George Herbert, The Temple: The Poetry of George Herbert\n|\nWenn man noch nicht den Menschen dienen kann, wie sollte man den Geistern dienen können?\n\n- Confucius, Gespräche\n|\nBy the time you swear you're his,Shivering and sighing.And he vows his passion is,Infinite, undying.Lady make note of this --One of you is lying.\n\n- Dorothy\n|\nWhen you fall for your appetite too early, you may not be able to endure to the end.\n\n- Israelmore Ayivor, Become a Better You\n|\nIf you wish to be happy,Eragon, Think not of what is to come nor of that which you have no control over but rather of the now and that which you are able to change\n\n- Christopher Paolini, Brisingr\n|\nI would fight dragons, I would walk over flaming coals, I would enter the Valley of the Dead, if I thought I might have a chance of your heart.\n\n- Julian Fellowes, Belgravia\n|\nThere are many forms of love as there is moments in time, and you are capable of feeling them all at different stages of your life.\n\n- Shannon\n|\nKnowing something is just something, until you apply your knowledge to make it everything.\n\n- Tahir\n|\nMerry hearts are vulnerable to death, don't be over-joyed to the state of oblivion, lest the enemy poison your meal.\n\n- Michael\n|\nToday, I will look around & enjoy all the beautiful things that are around me rather than yearn for things that are beyond my control & become miserable.-RVM\n\n- RVM\n|\nLa felicità non consiste nel mettersi al riparo dalla sofferenza, ma di integrarla al tessuto della nostra esistenza.\n\n- Éric-Emmanuel Schmitt, Invisible Love\n|\nI was burdened with an ever-growing heart on the verge of decay. To save myself, I had to give many pieces of my love away. I hope I can give it all to someone, someday.\n\n- Hubert\n|\nWords are like people, I think. Put too many of them too close together and they cause trouble.\n\n- Carolee Dean, Take Me There\n|\nOne has to take a somewhat bold and dangerous line with this existence: especially as, whatever happens, we are bound to lose it.\n\n- Friedrich Nietzsche, Untimely Meditations\n|\nGeorgie, stop trying to resurrect the shoes. They were never alive in the first place.\n\n- Ilona Andrews, On the Edge\n|\nLove drips like honey from the hive, constant, sweet, precious, into your heart each and every moment if you let it.\n\n- Amy\n|\nTo become great you have to be good first, and that only occurs by applying yourself. Commit to your passion and refuse to let yourself down.\n\n- Tyconis\n|\nI learned from the age of two or three that any room in our house, at any time of day, was there to read in, or be read to.\n\n- Eudora Welty, One Writer's Beginnings\n|\nRather than wait to see what the day or future holds, why not design and create it?\n\n- Mensah\n|\nYour wife is smarter than you; know this, and you will live happily ever after.\n\n- Matshona\n|\nWhen a writer tries to explain too much, he's out of time before he begins.\n\n- Isaac\n|\n...because all happiness is contagious, and disarms the spirit of hatred.\n\n- Irène Némirovsky, Suite Française\n|\nThere's so much to be grateful for, words are poor things.\n\n- Marilynne Robinson, Home\n|\nWe are often taught to look for the beauty in all things, so in finding it, the layman asks the philosopher while the philosopher asks the photographer.\n\n- Criss Jami, Killosophy\n|\nConsider the Lichen. Lichens are just about the hardiest visible organisms on Earth, but the least ambitious.\n\n- Bill Bryson, A Short History of Nearly Everything\n|\nYou know, there are two good things in life, freedom of thought and freedom of action.\n\n- W. Somerset Maugham, Of Human Bondage by Somerset Maugham\n|\nFreedom, you see, is having events go in accordance with our will, never contrary to it.\n\n- Epictetus, Discourses and Selected Writings\n|\nI can hardly wait for tomorrow, it means a new life for me each and every day.\n\n- Stanley\n|\nMan was created to glorify God. Now, that may encompass other things which God has planned for each man, but essentially, man was created to glorify God.\n\n- Criss Jami, Killosophy\n|\nFor, truly, the man who does not know when to die, does not know how to live.\n\n- John Ruskin, Unto This Last\n|\nDo not delay your happiness, be glad in the moment.\n\n- Lailah\n|\nI believe entertainment can aspire to be art, and can become art, but if you set out to make art you're an idiot.\n\n- Steve\n|\nDo not fear the conflict, and do not flee from it; where there is no struggle, there is no Virtue.\n\n- Joyram\n|\nIt is too late.' The old man shook his head. 'It is never too late or too soon. It is when it is supposed to be.' He smiled. 'There is a plan, Dor.\n\n- Mitch Albom, The Time Keeper\n|\nYour knowledge can stir the world, your intellect can move it, your wisdom can shake it, but only your love can truly change it.\n\n- Matshona\n|\nLife into death— Life’s other shape, No rupture, Only crossing.\n\n- Dejan Stojanovic, Circling: 1978-1987\n|\nIf wine is the enemy of religion, I shall devour the enemy of religion.\n\n- Idries Shah, Sufi Thought and Action\n|\nShe chose messy, she chose wild. She chose life on her own terms.\n\n- Liz  Newman, Hope Between Heartbeats"